docs.abstract: From “American Dirt” to “Apropos of Nothing” to “A Promised Land,” here is what happened in the literary and publishing world’s unforgettable 2020.
docs.snippet: From “American Dirt” to “Apropos of Nothing” to “A Promised Land,” here is what happened in the literary and publishing world’s unforgettable 2020.
docs.lead_paragraph: The year in books, like the year everywhere else, was a simultaneously breakneck and slow-motion mixture of exhaustion, peril, controversy, inspiration and resilience.

headline.main: How Politics, Protests and the Pandemic Shaped a Year in Books

docs.abstract: Among the last in her community, an 89-year-old woman self-published a memoir about life in the mountains, where a number of Black families settled after the end of the Civil War.
docs.snippet: Among the last in her community, an 89-year-old woman self-published a memoir about life in the mountains, where a number of Black families settled after the end of the Civil War.
docs.lead_paragraph: Mary Othella Burnette was born and raised in western North Carolina, in a small community in the mountains where a number of Black families settled after the end of the Civil War. Enslaved people, newly freed from local plantations, put down roots there, and Ms. Burnette is related to many of the earliest settlers of what is known as Southern Appalachia.

headline.main: Inside One Woman’s Quest to Preserve the Disappearing Southern Appalachia

docs.abstract: In a year defined by a pandemic, protests and politics, “The Daily” sought out personal stories. Here’s a holiday playlist of the episodes that Michael Barbaro and our team can’t forget.
docs.snippet: In a year defined by a pandemic, protests and politics, “The Daily” sought out personal stories. Here’s a holiday playlist of the episodes that Michael Barbaro and our team can’t forget.
docs.lead_paragraph: In moments of crisis, the journalistic urge to chronicle and memorialize becomes a kind of civic duty. That’s what 2020 was for “The Daily.” A rolling catastrophe that summoned us — to track down the most memorable characters, the most searing sounds, the most unforgettable scenes.

docs.abstract: The union in a small New Jersey city punished the officers after they expressed support for two chiefs, both of whom are also Black.
docs.snippet: The union in a small New Jersey city punished the officers after they expressed support for two chiefs, both of whom are also Black.
docs.lead_paragraph: ENGLEWOOD, N.J. — The tensions within the Englewood Police Department had simmered for months: at disciplinary hearings, during Black Lives Matter marches and in the fallout over no-confidence votes by the officers’ union in the chief and deputy chief.

headline.main: This Police Union Suspended 8 Members. Seven Are Black.
headline.print_headline: In Divided Department, Police Union Suspends 8  Who Supported 2 Chiefs

docs.abstract: With muscle injuries rising and an unforgiving, pandemic-compressed schedule looming, Europe might not crown its best team this season, but the one that’s still standing.
docs.snippet: With muscle injuries rising and an unforgiving, pandemic-compressed schedule looming, Europe might not crown its best team this season, but the one that’s still standing.
docs.lead_paragraph: The procession was nearly over. Ninety-five of the 96 games that constitute the group phase of the Champions League, six weeks of phony war that largely serve to check boxes, cross Ts and dot Is, were complete. Most of the heavyweights had long since advanced to the knockout rounds.

headline.main: The Champions League’s New Twist: Injury Roulette
headline.print_headline: Injury Roulette Adds Drama To Champions League Procession

docs.abstract: Joe Biden promised to be a president for all Americans. Here’s a way to start.
docs.snippet: Joe Biden promised to be a president for all Americans. Here’s a way to start.
docs.lead_paragraph: Joe Biden won the presidency because, at a moment when so many Americans were exhausted by the chaos and nastiness of the Trump era, he promised stability, decency and healing. At the heart of his candidacy was the vow to be “a president for all Americans” as he labored “to restore the soul of the nation.”

docs.abstract: “I look back with remorse,” Mayor Bill de Blasio said after a city oversight agency found the department’s tactics “produced excessive enforcement.”
docs.snippet: “I look back with remorse,” Mayor Bill de Blasio said after a city oversight agency found the department’s tactics “produced excessive enforcement.”
docs.lead_paragraph: The New York Police Department badly mishandled protests against police brutality over the summer, engaging in “excessive enforcement” that only heightened tensions with demonstrators, according to a report from a city oversight agency released on Friday.

headline.main: An Unprepared N.Y.P.D. Badly Mishandled Floyd Protests, Watchdog Says
headline.print_headline: Police Faulted Over Protests In New York

docs.abstract: The throngs of visitors have disappeared from New York City’s famous neighborhood, and there is an eeriness to the emptiness.
docs.snippet: The throngs of visitors have disappeared from New York City’s famous neighborhood, and there is an eeriness to the emptiness.
docs.lead_paragraph: A tour bus agent desperately tried to discern which passers-by were New Yorkers and which ones were out-of-towners. Newlyweds from Maryland, hoping to celebrate their nuptials with a special dinner, had to settle for McDonald’s. Four homeless men sat on a sidewalk, sharing cigarettes and a pipe filled with marijuana.

headline.main: Without Crowds, Is Times Square Really Times Square? Take a Look
headline.print_headline: If There Are No Crowds, Is It Still Times Square?
